  Since your app is workflow-based and already has **Frontend → Backend → Worker** architecture, I'd create **different dashboards for each service** instead of one giant dashboard. Each service has a different purpose, so the metrics you care about are different.

## 1. Backend Dashboard (API Service)

The backend mainly receives requests, validates them, creates workflows, and talks to the worker.

### Traffic

* Requests/sec (RPS)
* Total requests
* Active requests
* Request size
* Response size

### Latency

* P50 latency
* P95 latency
* P99 latency
* Slowest endpoints
* Endpoint-wise latency

### Errors

* Error rate (%)
* 4xx count
* 5xx count
* Exception count
* Top exceptions

### Resource Usage

* CPU %
* Memory
* GC collections (if .NET/Java)
* Thread count
* File descriptors

### Kubernetes

* Pod count
* Pod restarts
* OOMKills
* CPU throttling
* Network I/O

### Database (if backend accesses DB)

* Query latency
* Connection pool usage
* Failed queries

### OpenTelemetry

* Trace duration
* Top slow spans
* Requests by endpoint
* Trace waterfall

---

# 2. Worker Dashboard

This is the most important dashboard because actual execution happens here.

### Queue

* Queue length
* Jobs waiting
* Jobs processing
* Jobs completed/sec
* Jobs failed/sec
* Retry count

### Workflow Metrics

* Workflow execution time
* Step execution time
* Long-running workflows
* Success %
* Failure %
* Timeout count

### Resource Usage

* CPU
* Memory
* Network
* Disk I/O

### Errors

* Exceptions
* Failed jobs
* Retry rate
* Dead-letter queue size (if applicable)

### OpenTelemetry

* Workflow traces
* Span duration
* Longest-running spans
* External API calls
* Database spans

### Kubernetes

* Pod restarts
* Replica count
* HPA status
* Pending pods
* Node utilization

