# 5. End-to-End Dashboard

Since you're using OpenTelemetry, I'd also have one dashboard showing the full request journey:

```
Frontend
     │
     ▼
Backend
     │
     ▼
Queue
     │
     ▼
Worker
     │
     ▼
Database
```

Track:

* Total request duration
* Backend processing time
* Queue wait time
* Worker execution time
* DB time
* External API time
* Error location (where failures occur)

This quickly tells you whether latency is in the backend, queue, worker, or database.

---

## Recommended layout

### Backend Dashboard

* RPS
* Error %
* P95 latency
* CPU
* Memory
* Top endpoints
* Exceptions
* Pod health

### Worker Dashboard

* Active jobs
* Queue length
* Success/failure rate
* Workflow duration
* CPU
* Memory
* Retries
* Slow workflows

### Kubernetes Dashboard

* Cluster health
* Node CPU/Memory
* Pod health
* Restarts
* Network
* Deployments

### Trace Dashboard

* End-to-end request latency
* Span breakdown
* Slow traces
* Error traces
* Service dependency graph

This separation makes it much easier to diagnose issues: API problems show up on the backend dashboard, execution bottlenecks on the worker dashboard, infrastructure issues on the Kubernetes dashboard, and overall performance on the trace dashboard.
